<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{zutsu}}}} is a particle that indicates that a quantity is equally distributed.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{zutsu}}}} always follows a quantifier.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{dono@KT{{kurasu}}nimo@KJ{{woman^child^study^life}}ga@KJ{{six^person}}@EM{{zutsu}}ita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There were six girl students in each class.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{zutsu}}}} serves only focus on the equal distribution.
In the sentence below, it emphasises that the same number of kanji is learned every day.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{Sino-^character}}:kanji}}wo@KJ{{every^day^five}}tsu@EM{{zutsu}}@FG{{@KJ{{memorize}}:obo}}eru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I memorise five kanji every day.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If @HI{{@EM{{zutsu}}}} is removed from the sentence the meaning hardly changes. All that has been removed is the emphasis on the
equal distribution of kanji learned each day.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
